XIII. Atque hinc etiam intelligi potest exercitoriam et institoriam, quae non tam actiones sunt quam qualitates actio- num, ipso naturali jure niti. Adjiciendum hic est male Roma- nis legibus introductum, ut ex facto magistri exercitores in solidum singuli tenerentur. Nam hoc naturali aequitati con- venit, 1quae satis habet si pro suis singuli partibus conveni- antur, nec publice utile est: absterrentur enim homines ab exercendis navibus, si metuant ne ex facto magistri quasi in infinitum teneantur. Atque adeo apud Hollandos‚ ubi mer- catura pridem maxime viguit, et nunc et olim lex illa Romana observata non est: imo contra, constitutum, ne exercitoria. etiam universi amplius teneantur, quam ad aestimationem navis, et eorum quae in navi sunt.

XIII. Hence we may understand that an exercitorian action (one against ship-owners for the contracts of the captain,) and an insti- toriam action, (one against the owner of a trading concern for the con- tracts of the acting agent,) depend on Natural Law, being, not so much distinct kinds of action, as qualities of actions. But it has been im- properly added by the Roman Law, that all the ship-owners are bound severally, as well as jointly, by the acts of the captain. This is nei- ther in accordance with natural equity, which is satisfied if each owner is responsible for his own share3 nor useful to the public3 for persons are deterred from sending adventures in ships, if they are in fear that they may be indefinitely involved by the acts of the captain. And therefore in Holland, where commerce has long flourished, that Roman law neither prevailed formerly, nor does n0w3 on the contrary, it is the law that, inan exercitorian action, even the whole body of owners are not held responsible, beyond the value of the ship and eargo.
